    <div class="content">
        <h2>Hello!</h2>
        <p>Records indicate that you were recently compromised from our in-house phishing training. But do not worry! This training will help you find ways to protect both your own personal information and Western Express itself! <b1>The image directly below shows the phishing email you fell for: </b1> </p>
    </div>
    <div class="additional-image">
        <img src="https://i.imgur.com/iIAzcpB.png" alt="Additional Training Image" width="650">
    </div>
    <div class="additional-content">
        <h3>How to Determine if an Email or Website is a Phishing Attempt</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Check the sender's email address for discrepancies or suspicious domains.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: An email claims to be from PayPal, but the sender's address is "support@paypa1.com" (note the '1' instead of 'l').</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/6fh8hUC.png" alt="Example Image 1" width="600">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Look for generic greetings like "Dear Customer" instead of your name.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: "Dear Customer, your account has been compromised" instead of "Dear John Smith, your account has been compromised".</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/nrP7d0P.png" alt="Example Image 2" width="400">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Beware of urgent or threatening language designed to provoke an immediate response.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: "Your account will be suspended within 24 hours if you do not verify your information immediately."</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/zWPxTy9.png" alt="Example Image 3" width="500">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Hover over links to see the actual URL before clicking; phishing sites often have misspelled or unusual URLs.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: A link appears as "www.bankofamerica.com" but when you hover over it, it shows "www.bankofamerrica.com".</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/IJn3av5.png" alt="Example Image 4" width="350">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Examine the email for spelling and grammatical errors, which are common in phishing attempts.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: "Dear user, your acount has been temporaly locked. Please click here to unlock."</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/QhtHHYB.png" alt="Example Image 5" width="300">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Check for unexpected attachments or requests for personal information.</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: An email from a supposed friend includes an unexpected attachment labeled "Invoice" or asks for your Social Security number.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/KvmGCgk.png" alt="Example Image 6" width="400">
                </div>
            </li>
            <li>
                <div class="li-content">
                    <h4>Ensure the website has a secure connection (look for "https://" and a padlock icon).</h4>
                    <div class="example">Example: A legitimate site should display "https://" at the beginning of the URL, indicating a secure connection. Phishing sites often lack this.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="li-image">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/ygY845W.png" alt="Example Image 8" width="300">
                </div>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>

